Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Statistical Summary Observations

Income

  • Wide range ($8K – $224K) with a high mean (~$74K).
  • Suggests strong variation across customers, which could impact ability/willingness to take loans.

CCAvg (Credit Card Spending)

  • Right-skewed distribution, mean ~$1.9K but max at $10K.
  • Indicates a segment of heavy spenders who may be more likely to consider loans.

Education

  • Encoded as 1–3, with mean ~1.9.
  • Many customers are graduate or professional level, which often correlates with higher income and financial product adoption.

CD Account

  • Small proportion (~6%) of customers hold a CD account.
  • Even though minority, this feature stands out as it differentiates customers into distinct groups.

❓ Questions & Observations¶

1. What is the distribution of the mortgage attribute? Are there any noticeable patterns or outliers in the distribution?¶

  • The mortgage distribution is right-skewed, with most customers reporting low or no mortgage values.
  • A large proportion of customers have zero mortgage, suggesting many do not currently hold a home loan.
  • A small number of outliers with very high mortgage values exist, but these represent only a fraction of the customer base.

2. How many customers have credit cards?¶

  • A majority of customers have credit cards, while a smaller portion do not.
  • As a binary attribute, the distribution is imbalanced but still informative.
  • Credit card ownership may serve as a proxy for financial engagement and borrowing behavior.

3. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with the target attribute (personal loan)?¶

  • Income shows a strong positive correlation — higher income customers are more likely to accept personal loans.
  • CCAvg (average monthly credit card spending) is also strongly correlated — higher spenders are more inclined to borrow.
  • CD Account ownership is positively associated with loan acceptance.
  • Other attributes (age, experience, mortgage) show weak or negligible correlations.
  • Categorical variables (ZIP code, education, family) were excluded from the correlation heatmap.

4. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their age?¶

  • Loan acceptance is highest among customers aged 30–50.
  • Younger customers (<30) and older customers (>60) are less likely to take personal loans.
  • This trend suggests interest peaks during prime earning years, when financial needs (mortgages, children, investments) are greatest.

5. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their education?¶

  • Loan acceptance increases with higher education levels.
  • Customers with Graduate or Advanced/Professional degrees are more likely to accept loans compared to those with only an undergraduate degree.
  • This may reflect higher earning potential and greater financial literacy among more educated customers.

🔍 Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) — Key Observations¶

1. Target Variable Distribution¶

  • The dataset is imbalanced: only ~9.6% of customers accepted the personal loan offer (personal_loan = 1), while the majority (~90.4%) did not.
  • This imbalance has important implications for model building: we must prioritize recall to ensure loan accepters are not missed.

2. Continuous Variables¶

  • Age & Experience: Both are normally distributed around the mid-40s. Some negative experience values were identified and corrected.
  • Income: Right-skewed distribution; a small group of very high-income customers exists (potential influencers of model performance).
  • CCAvg (Credit Card Spending): Right-skewed; most customers spend modestly, while a small number spend significantly more.
  • Mortgage: Many customers have no mortgage (0 value). Among those with mortgages, values are widely spread with some large outliers.

3. Categorical Variables¶

  • Family Size: Distribution is fairly even across categories (1–4). Slightly higher representation for smaller families.
  • Education: Most customers are undergraduates; however, customers with advanced/professional education show higher interest in loans.
  • Region: Derived from ZIP code (first 2 digits). Regions are reasonably well distributed without extreme imbalance.
  • Binary Flags (Securities Account, CD Account, Online, Credit Card):
    • Majority of customers do not hold securities or CDs.
    • Online banking usage is common (~60%).
    • Only ~29% have a credit card with another bank.

4. Bivariate Analysis¶

  • Loan Acceptance vs Income: Higher income customers are much more likely to accept personal loans.
  • Loan Acceptance vs Education: Loan acceptance is strongly correlated with higher education levels (graduate, advanced/professional).
  • Loan Acceptance vs Age/Experience: No strong relationship; acceptance is relatively consistent across age groups.
  • Loan Acceptance vs Family Size: No clear trend; family size does not appear to be a key driver.
  • Loan Acceptance vs Credit Card Spending (CCAvg): Higher spending customers show higher loan acceptance rates.

5. Correlation Heatmap¶

  • Strong correlation between Income and CCAvg, as expected.
  • Personal Loan shows moderate positive correlation with Income, CCAvg, and CD Account.
  • No significant correlation between personal_loan and variables such as age, family size, or securities account.

6. Statistical Tests (Chi-Square)¶

  • Categorical features such as Education, Region, CD Account, Online, and Credit Card show statistically significant association with loan acceptance (p < 0.05).
  • Family size has a weaker relationship with loan acceptance.

📌 Overall EDA Insights¶

  • Customers more likely to accept personal loans are characterized by:
    • Higher income
    • Higher credit card spending (CCAvg)
    • Graduate or advanced education
    • Holding a CD account
  • These findings will help in feature selection and business targeting strategies.
  • The strong imbalance in the target variable confirms the need to focus on recall when building models.

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

In [21]:
# ============================
# Extended Model Evaluation
# ============================

from sklearn.metrics import (accuracy_score, recall_score, precision_score,
                             f1_score, roc_auc_score, confusion_matrix)
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

def model_performance_classification(model, X, y, name="Model"):
    """
    Compute Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1, ROC-AUC for a classification model
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    y_proba = model.predict_proba(X)[:,1] if hasattr(model, "predict_proba") else None

    acc = accuracy_score(y, y_pred)
    rec = recall_score(y, y_pred)
    pre = precision_score(y, y_pred)
    f1  = f1_score(y, y_pred)
    roc = roc_auc_score(y, y_proba) if y_proba is not None else np.nan

    return pd.DataFrame({
        "Model": [name],
        "Accuracy": [acc],
        "Recall": [rec],
        "Precision": [pre],
        "F1": [f1],
        "ROC-AUC": [roc]
    })

def plot_cm(model, X, y, title="Confusion Matrix"):
    """
    Plot confusion matrix with counts + percentages
    """
    y_pred = model.predict(X)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
    cm_sum = cm.sum()
    labels = np.asarray([[f"{v}\n{v/cm_sum:.2%}" for v in row] for row in cm])

    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
                xticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"],
                yticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"])
    plt.ylabel("True label")
    plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

def plot_cm_train_test(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, title_prefix="Confusion Matrix"):
    """
    Plot Train and Test confusion matrices side-by-side (counts + percentages)
    """
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,5))
    for (name, X, y, ax) in [("Train", X_train, y_train, axes[0]),
                             ("Test",  X_test,  y_test,  axes[1])]:
        y_pred = model.predict(X)
        cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)
        cm_sum = cm.sum()
        labels = np.asarray([[f"{v}\n{v/cm_sum:.2%}" for v in row] for row in cm])
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
                    xticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"],
                    yticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"],
                    ax=ax)
        ax.set_title(f"{title_prefix} — {name}")
        ax.set_xlabel("Predicted label")
        ax.set_ylabel("True label")
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def evaluate_model_train_test(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, name="Model", plot=False):
    """
    Return train & test metrics; optionally plot side-by-side confusion matrices.
    """
    perf_train = model_performance_classification(model, X_train, y_train, name=name+" (Train)")
    perf_test  = model_performance_classification(model, X_test,  y_test,  name=name+" (Test)")
    results = pd.concat([perf_train, perf_test], ignore_index=True)
    if plot:
        plot_cm_train_test(model, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, title_prefix=name)
    return results

perf_dt_pre = evaluate_model_train_test(best_dt_pre, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test,
                                        name="DT — Pre-Pruned", plot=True)
print(perf_dt_pre)

Model Evaluation Helpers¶

Since our business goal is to maximize recall (catch as many loan accepters as possible), we need consistent tools to evaluate models.
We will track the following metrics for each model:

  • Recall (priority) → ability to correctly identify customers who accept loans.
  • Precision → proportion of predicted loan-acceptors that are correct.
  • F1-score → harmonic mean of recall and precision.
  • Accuracy → overall correctness (less important due to class imbalance).
  • ROC-AUC → ability to separate classes across thresholds.
  • Confusion Matrix → shows true/false positives and negatives, with percentages.

The helper functions below will standardize these evaluations.

# =========================================
# Decision Tree Trio (Base / Pre / Post)
# Assumptions:
# - df2 already contains 'region' (from zipcode first 2 digits) and no 'zipcode'
# - Keep BOTH 'age' and 'experience' (experience negatives clipped to 0)
# - Evaluation helpers are defined: model_performance_classification, plot_cm
# =========================================

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split, GridSearchCV
from sklearn.compose import ColumnTransformer
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, plot_tree

# -----------------------------
# 0) Modeling prep (simple & safe)
# -----------------------------
dfm = df2.copy()

# Keep both age & experience; only fix negatives in experience
if 'experience' in dfm.columns:
    dfm['experience'] = dfm['experience'].clip(lower=0)

# Features / target
X = dfm.drop(columns=['personal_loan'])
y = dfm['personal_loan']

# Column groups (ensure region is categorical; zipcode is already gone)
cat_cols = [c for c in ['family','education','region'] if c in X.columns]
bin_cols = [c for c in ['securities_account','cd_account','online','creditcard'] if c in X.columns]
num_cols = [c for c in ['age','experience','income','ccavg','mortgage'] if c in X.columns]

# One-hot encode categoricals; numerics & binaries passthrough (trees don't need scaling)
preprocessor = ColumnTransformer(
    transformers=[('cat', OneHotEncoder(drop='first', handle_unknown='ignore'), cat_cols)],
    remainder='passthrough'
)

# Stratified split due to class imbalance
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

# Utility to recover feature names after ColumnTransformer (for importances / plotting)
def get_feature_names_after_ct(cat_cols, num_cols, bin_cols, fitted_pipe):
    ohe = fitted_pipe.named_steps['prep'].named_transformers_['cat']
    cat_names = ohe.get_feature_names_out(cat_cols) if cat_cols else np.array([])
    remainder_names = np.array(num_cols + bin_cols)
    return np.concatenate([cat_names, remainder_names])

# ==========================================================
# 1) Decision Tree — Base Model (no pruning, true baseline)
#    Keep defaults to show baseline behavior. No class_weight.
# ==========================================================
dt_base = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('prep', preprocessor),
    ('model', DecisionTreeClassifier(
        criterion='gini',
        random_state=42
    ))
])
dt_base.fit(X_train, y_train)

perf_base = model_performance_classification(dt_base, X_test, y_test, name="DT — Base")
print(perf_base)
plot_cm(dt_base, X_test, y_test, title="DT — Base")

# Optional: quick preview plot at shallow depth for readability
try:
    feat_names = get_feature_names_after_ct(cat_cols, num_cols, bin_cols, dt_base)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))
    out = plot_tree(dt_base.named_steps['model'], feature_names=feat_names,
                    class_names=["No","Yes"], filled=True, fontsize=8, max_depth=3)
    # Add arrows (FAQ tip)
    for o in out:
        arrow = getattr(o, "arrow_patch", None)
        if arrow is not None:
            arrow.set_edgecolor('black')
            arrow.set_linewidth(1)
    plt.title("DT — Base (Preview, max_depth=3)")
    plt.show()
except Exception as e:
    print("Tree preview skipped:", e)

# ==========================================================
# 2) Decision Tree — Pre-Pruning
#    Constrain complexity BEFORE overfitting; use class_weight='balanced' to lift recall.
# ==========================================================
dt_pre = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('prep', preprocessor),
    ('model', DecisionTreeClassifier(
        criterion='gini',
        class_weight='balanced',
        random_state=42
    ))
])

param_grid_pre = {
    'model__max_depth': [3, 4, 5, 6, 8, None],
    'model__min_samples_split': [2, 10, 25],
    'model__min_samples_leaf': [1, 5, 10, 20],
}

grid_pre = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=dt_pre,
    param_grid=param_grid_pre,
    scoring='recall',   # <<< maximize recall
    cv=5,
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=0
)
grid_pre.fit(X_train, y_train)

best_dt_pre = grid_pre.best_estimator_
print("Pre-Pruning best params:", grid_pre.best_params_)
print("Pre-Pruning CV Recall:", round(grid_pre.best_score_, 4))

perf_pre = model_performance_classification(best_dt_pre, X_test, y_test, name="DT — Pre-Pruned")
print(perf_pre)
plot_cm(best_dt_pre, X_test, y_test, title="DT — Pre-Pruned")

# ==========================================================
# 3) Decision Tree — Post-Pruning (Cost-Complexity, ccp_alpha)
#    Fit, compute pruning path alphas, then cross-validate ccp_alpha for best recall.
# ==========================================================
# Fit preprocessor on training to get transformed X for pruning path
X_train_transformed = preprocessor.fit_transform(X_train)

dt_for_path = DecisionTreeClassifier(
    criterion='gini',
    class_weight='balanced',
    random_state=42
)
# Use the transformed training set to compute pruning path
path = dt_for_path.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train_transformed, y_train)
# FAQ note: take absolute values
ccp_alphas_raw = np.abs(path.ccp_alphas)
ccp_alphas_raw = np.unique(ccp_alphas_raw)

# Candidate alphas (exclude last which prunes to root)
if len(ccp_alphas_raw) > 1:
    ccp_alphas = ccp_alphas_raw[:-1]
else:
    ccp_alphas = ccp_alphas_raw

# Subsample to ~25 alphas if many
step = max(1, len(ccp_alphas)//25)
ccp_candidates = list(ccp_alphas[::step]) if len(ccp_alphas) > 0 else [0.0]
if 0.0 not in ccp_candidates:
    ccp_candidates = [0.0] + ccp_candidates

dt_post = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('prep', preprocessor),  # refit inside CV folds
    ('model', DecisionTreeClassifier(
        criterion='gini',
        class_weight='balanced',
        random_state=42
    ))
])

param_grid_post = {'model__ccp_alpha': ccp_candidates}

grid_post = GridSearchCV(
    estimator=dt_post,
    param_grid=param_grid_post,
    scoring='recall',   # <<< maximize recall
    cv=5,
    n_jobs=-1,
    verbose=0
)
grid_post.fit(X_train, y_train)

best_dt_post = grid_post.best_estimator_
print("Post-Pruning best ccp_alpha:", grid_post.best_params_)
print("Post-Pruning CV Recall:", round(grid_post.best_score_, 4))

perf_post = model_performance_classification(best_dt_post, X_test, y_test, name="DT — Post-Pruned")
print(perf_post)
plot_cm(best_dt_post, X_test, y_test, title="DT — Post-Pruned")

# -----------------------------
# 4) Compare the three models
# -----------------------------
perf_table = pd.concat([perf_base, perf_pre, perf_post], ignore_index=True)
display(perf_table.sort_values('Recall', ascending=False))

🔧 Model Performance Improvement¶

Our initial Decision Tree models provided valuable insights:

  • Pre-Pruned DT maximized recall (1.0) but suffered from very low precision (~0.31).
  • Base DT achieved high precision (~0.90) but failed to meet our recall objective (~0.92).
  • Post-Pruned DT simplified the tree but reduced discriminative power (ROC-AUC ~0.89).

To improve performance while prioritizing recall, we can explore several techniques:

  1. Probability Threshold Tuning – adjust the decision threshold to balance recall and precision.
  2. Ensemble Models – use Random Forests, Gradient Boosted Trees (XGBoost/LightGBM) for more robust recall.
  3. Feature Engineering – create interaction terms or bin continuous variables (e.g., income groups).
  4. Class Imbalance Handling – apply SMOTE, undersampling, or cost-sensitive learning.
  5. Model Comparison – benchmark tree-based models against Logistic Regression and Ensemble methods.

from sklearn.metrics import precision_recall_curve, confusion_matrix, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score, accuracy_score
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# --- 1) Choose your recall target ---
RECALL_TARGET = 1.00  # try 1.00 (strict) or relax slightly to 0.99

# --- 2) Get scores, sweep thresholds, and pick the best threshold under the recall constraint ---
y_true = y_test
y_score = best_dt_pre.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1]

precision, recall, thresholds = precision_recall_curve(y_true, y_score)
# precision_recall_curve returns thresholds of length n-1; align with metrics
thr = np.r_[0.0, thresholds]  # include 0.0 so arrays align

# Keep thresholds meeting recall target; among them, pick the one with max precision
mask = recall >= RECALL_TARGET
if mask.any():
    idx = np.argmax(precision[mask])        # index within the masked array
    best_threshold = thr[mask][idx]
else:
    # if nothing meets the strict target, fall back to threshold that maximizes recall
    best_threshold = thr[np.argmax(recall)]

print(f"Selected threshold: {best_threshold:.3f} (Recall target ≥ {RECALL_TARGET})")

# --- 3) Evaluate at the chosen threshold ---
y_pred_tuned = (y_score >= best_threshold).astype(int)

acc  = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred_tuned)
rec  = recall_score(y_true, y_pred_tuned)
pre  = precision_score(y_true, y_pred_tuned, zero_division=0)
f1   = f1_score(y_true, y_pred_tuned)
cm   = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred_tuned)

print(pd.DataFrame([{
    "Model": "DT — Pre-Pruned (Threshold-Tuned)",
    "Threshold": best_threshold,
    "Accuracy": acc,
    "Recall": rec,
    "Precision": pre,
    "F1": f1
}]))

# --- 4) Confusion matrix at tuned threshold (counts + percentages) ---
cm_sum = cm.sum()
labels = np.asarray([[f"{v}\n{v/cm_sum:.2%}" for v in row] for row in cm])

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues", cbar=False,
            xticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"],
            yticklabels=["No Loan (0)", "Loan (1)"])
plt.title("DT — Pre-Pruned (Threshold-Tuned) — Test Set")
plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
plt.ylabel("True label")
plt.show()

# --- 5) (Optional) Visualize the Precision–Recall vs Threshold to see trade-offs ---
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12,4))
ax[0].plot(thr, recall, label="Recall")
ax[0].axhline(RECALL_TARGET, ls="--", color="gray")

⚖️ Threshold Tuning Results — The Recall vs Precision Dilemma¶

The probability threshold tuning test on the Pre-Pruned Decision Tree produced the following insights:

  • At a threshold of 0.0, the model achieves perfect recall (1.0) — it identifies every actual loan accepter.
  • However, this comes at a steep cost:
    • Precision drops to ~0.10 → only ~1 in 10 predicted "loan takers" actually accepts a loan.
    • Accuracy collapses to ~9.6%, because the model predicts "Loan" for everyone.
    • The confusion matrix confirms this: all 1,356 non-loan customers are misclassified as loan accepters.

The threshold plots clearly show the trade-off:

  • Recall vs Threshold: Recall starts at 1.0 and declines as the threshold increases.
  • Precision vs Threshold: Precision starts very low at threshold 0.0 and rises as the threshold increases.

📌 The Dilemma¶

We cannot simultaneously maximize both recall and precision:

  • If we set the threshold very low (e.g., 0.0):
    We guarantee recall = 1.0, but overwhelm the campaign with false positives (low precision, wasted marketing effort).

  • If we raise the threshold:
    Precision improves (fewer wasted offers), but recall drops below 1.0, meaning some potential loan customers will be missed.

✅ The Required Choice¶

The business must decide which is more costly:

  1. Missing potential loan customers (lower recall), or
  2. Targeting many uninterested customers (lower precision).

For this project, the campaign objective was to maximize recall. Therefore, the recall-first approach is chosen — ensuring no potential loan customer is missed, even at the cost of reduced efficiency.
Future improvements (e.g., probability threshold tuning with a relaxed recall target, ensemble models, or segmentation) can help recover precision without sacrificing too much recall.

Key Observations¶

  • Recall:
    Both Pre-Pruned and Post-Pruned trees achieved 100% recall, meaning all loan accepters were identified. This fully aligns with the campaign’s business goal.
  • Precision:
    Precision was significantly lower for the Pre-/Post-Pruned models (~31%) compared to the Base model (~90%). This indicates more false positives, translating into higher marketing costs.
  • Accuracy:
    The Base model achieved very high accuracy (~98%) but recall was below 1.0, meaning some potential customers would be missed.
  • Model Stability:
    Train vs Test metrics for all three models were consistent, showing no major overfitting.

Final Model Selection¶

Given that the business objective is to maximize recall (do not miss any loan accepters), the Decision Tree — Pre-Pruned model is selected as the final model.

  • It ensures 100% recall, capturing every potential loan-taker.
  • While precision is low, this trade-off is acceptable since the cost of missing a loan customer is higher than the cost of additional outreach.
  • Pre-Pruning also provides more stability and interpretability compared to the Post-Pruned version.

Final Recommendation:
Use the Pre-Pruned Decision Tree as the chosen model, while planning future improvements (threshold tuning, ensemble models, segmentation) to raise precision without sacrificing recall.

🎯 Why Recall Was Prioritized¶

For this project, recall was selected as the key evaluation metric.

  • Business Rationale: In the bank’s personal loan campaign, missing out on a potential loan customer (a false negative) is more costly than contacting an uninterested customer (a false positive).
  • Model Implications: A recall-focused model ensures that all true loan accepters are captured, even if it means lowering precision.
  • Analogy: Similar to a medical screening test, the model must identify every possible "positive case" (loan accepter) so that none are missed, even if some "false alarms" occur.

This aligns directly with the campaign’s goal: maximize conversion opportunities for personal loans while managing marketing costs.
